leads.lead_text: Ovary attenuated, cylindric to narrow obovoid, appressed to rachis
Ovary short, obovoid to pyriform, not appressed to rachis
Labellum bent at an angle greater than 90 deg., basal portion pouched, callus ending in two protruding knuckles
Labellum bent at an angle less than 90 deg., basal portion not pouched, callus not ending in protruding knuckles
Leaf-blade more than 3 cm long; labellum margins voluminous, not incurved; tubers ovoid
Leaf-blade less than 3 cm long; labellum margins narrow, incurved; tubers rhizomatous
Labellum lamina and/or callus papillate or pubescent
Labellum lamina and callus not papillate or pubescent
Flower spikes dense with flowers overlapping; petals strongly recurved; subalpine
Flower spikes not dense with flowers not overlapping; petals not strongly recurved; lowland plants (except rarely in P. lindleyanum)
Labellum with a sigmoid bend when viewed from the side
Labellum bent once at about 90 deg. near the middle
Ovaries tumid, short and roundish at anthesis
Ovaries not tumid, narrow ellipsoidal at anthesis
Perianth segments usually not widely opening, at least petals remaining forwards-directed; labellum lamina pink (sometimes fading to white with age) with a green callus
Perianth segments spreading; labellum lamina whitish with a brownish callus, or labellum (and usually other segments) deep pink to purple and shining
Labellum lamina, and usually other floral segments, deep pink to purplish, distinctly glossy; callus of similar colour but darker
Labellum lamina pale green or whitish with a brownish callus, neither it nor other segments distinctly glossy
Lateral sepals more or less parallel, narrow and not flared at the base; labellum <3 mm wide, recurved near midde then the tip recurved beyond vertical; known only from Stawell area
Lateral sepals spreading, broad and flared widely at the base; labellum >3 mm wide, recurved near middle and the tip remaining about vertical; known only from Edenhope area
Labellum callus hardly raised, lamina prominently crisped and undulate toward margin, usually white, translucent
Labellum callus distinctly raised, lamina not prominently crisped, variously coloured, not translucent
Lateral sepals joined for at least part of their length
Lateral sepals free to base
Labellum reflexed back on itself; not alpine
Labellum reflexed at about 90 deg; alpine
Flowers densely crowded; flowering stem to 80 cm high; lowland heaths
Flowers not densely crowded; flowering stem usually <50 cm tall; various habitats
Petals lavender; labellum pink; lateral sepals gibbous at base; Bayswater to Heathmont east of Melbourne where probably extinct
Combination of flower features not as above; widespread and variable
Ovaries short, pyriform; labellum narrow, reflexed at more than right angles near middle; alps and subalps only
Ovaries somewhat elongate, obovoid;  if labellum ever reflexed beyond right-angles, habitat not alpine
Sepals to 10 mm long; labellum 6–10 mm long; widespread species from a range of habitats
Sepals 10–12 mm long; labellum 12–15 mm long; known only from grassland in north-central Victoria and Callitris woodlands of the north-west
Lateral sepals diverging; habitat various but not from deep sands in north-western Victoria
Lateral sepals parallel or very nearly so; known with certainty only from deep sand mallee-heath in north-western Victoria
Labellum callus most prominent near the labellum bend, not extending to labellum apex; perianth segments generally short and broad; lateral sepals usually free
Labellum callus most prominent beyond the labellum bend, extending almost to labellum apex; perianth segments slender; lateral sepals often joined at least near base
Labellum with a tail-like caudiform apex
Labellum with an apiculate to obtuse apex
Perianth mostly incurved; labellum callus ending in a highly raised verrucose horse-shoe shaped structure
Perianth spreading widely; labellum callus not as above
Labellum callus extending to, or just beyond, bend; labellum lamina extending well beyond end of callus
Labellum callus extending well beyond bend; labellum lamina not extending well beyond end of callus
Petals <7.0 mm long; lateral sepals <9.0 mm long; flowers December to January
Petals >7.5 mm long; lateral sepals >9.0 mm long; flowers October to November
Callus ovate-oblong, broad and open; petals very broad, whitish, similar in colour to labellum lamina
Callus lanceolate, channelled; petals narrow, greenish, similar in colour to the lateral sepals
Labellum margins crisped to undulate; petals broad, similar in colour to labellum lamina
Labellum margins entire to slightly irregular; petals narrow, similar in colour to the lateral sepals
Labellum laterally compressed near bend; petals whitish; moist grassland near water-courses
Labellum not laterally compressed; petals reddish; coastal heath and scrub on sand
Lateral sepals partially connate;  alpine herbfields; flowers mostly January
Lateral sepals free to base; low altitude grasslands; flowers October to December
Lateral sepals more or less parallel; labellum lamina usually white, not constricted; grasslands south of Ballarat
Lateral sepals diverging; labellum lamina usually pink, often constricted just beyond the bend; grasslands near Warrnambool
Flowers opening widely with petals and sepals reflexed; labellum erect almost from base
Flowers not opening widely; labellum only erect from the bend
Petals retroflexed and not upswept; lateral sepal < 6mm long
Petals recurved and upswept; lateral sepals > 6 mm long
Inflorescence of up to 20 flowers in an open inflorescence; stigmatic plate much longer than column wings; grasslands near Bairnsdale
Inflorescence of up to 50 flowers in a crowded inflorescence; stigmatic plate of similar length to column wings; grasslands near Mortlake
Labellum with a broad white lamina; petals with extensive white colouration at distal end; grasslands near Wangaratta
Labellum and petals not as above; widespread
Plants from higher altitude grasslands, herbfields and swampy heaths often on peaty soils
Plants from lower altitude sites, or if in montane areas then in dry woodlands on shallow soils
Sepals to 6.5 mm long; labellum sessile
Sepals > 6.5 mm long; labellum on a short stalk
Plants from well-drained shallow or dry sandy soils
Plants from waterlogged or seasonally inundated heavy loams, silts, peats or peaty sand
Flowers <12 mm × 7 mm
Flowers >12 mm × 7 mm
Labellum callus with a deep groove down centre for entire length; apex of lateral sepals often unequally bidentate
Labellum callus not deeply grooved for the greater part; apex of lateral sepals not or weakly bidentate
Lateral sepals connate at base; coastal heathlands east of French Island
Lateral sepals mostly free; woodlands and heathy woodlands of western Victoria
Plants usually >16 cm tall; flowers >10 per inflorescence; dry inland areas
Plants usually <16 cm tall; flowers <10 per inflorescence; mesic near coastal areas
Apex of lateral sepals usually strongly bidentate
Apex of lateral sepals not or only weakly bidentate
Labellum margins entire or slightly irregular; lateral sepals >8 mm long
Labellum margins irregularly wavy to crinkled-crenulate; lateral sepals 6–7.5 mm long
Distal margins of labellum irregularly crenulate
Distal margins of labellum entire or slightly irregular
Labellum callus wrinkled; perianth segments relatively broad, usually greenish brown; labellum lamina not pure white
Labellum callus not wrinkled; perianth segments relatively narrow, usually light greenish; labellum lamina white
Flowers <20 mm long; labellum tapering gradually from below the middle to the apex, margins broad and often conspicuously veined; petals tapering from base to apex
Flowers often >20 mm long; labellum abruptly contracted near middle to a slender tail-like tip, margins not as above; petals not tapering from base to apex
Flowers to 15 mm long; plants of near coastal forests
Flowers >15 mm long; plants of inland open forests and woodlands
Distal labellum margins undulate to crenulate
Distal labellum margins entire, more or less flat to slightly irregular
Flowers to 12 × 7 mm; distal labellum margins undulate and narrow; native pine and buloke woodlands on wet loams and cracking clay; flowers September
Flowers >12 × 7 mm; distal labellum margins undulate to crenulate, relatively broad
Distal labellum margins crinkled-crenulate and of moderate width; flowers usually green to brownish; flowers August to September
Distal labellum margins undulate-crispate, voluminous; flowers usually bright pink and white; flowers November to December
Flowers to 12 × 6 mm
Flowers >12 × 6 mm
Labellum narrow, length to width ratio >2; labellum lamina <0.3 mm wide
Labellum broader than above, length to width ratio <2; labellum lamina >0.4 mm wide
Lateral sepals 2–3 mm long; labellum protruding forward and strongly reflexed in distal third; southern Victorian basalt plains grassland; flowers October to November
Lateral sepals 5–7 mm long; labellum erect and only slightly reflexed in distal third; northern Victorian grasslands on winter-wet heavy clays; flowers August to September
Labellum reflexed at <90 deg. in distal half; lateral sepals not bidentate at apex; plants not clumping; River Red Gum woodlands on water-retentive clay; flowers October to November
Labellum reflexed at >90 deg. in distal half; lateral sepals often bidentate at apex; plants often clumping; southern Victorian basalt plains grassland; flowers September to October
Perianth segments thin-textured; lateral sepals contracting abruptly; River Red Gum woodlands on water-retentive clay; north-east Victoria; flowers October to November
Perianth segments thick-textured; lateral sepals tapering evenly from base to apex; habitat not as above
Lateral sepals with acute to shortly acuminate, widely diverging apices; flowers to 9 mm across; petals to 8.5 mm long; swampy habitats; western Victoria; flowers December to January
Lateral sepals with long-acuminate, not widely diverging apices; flowers 9 mm across or more; petals 9 mm long or more; dryer habitats; eastern Victoria; flowers October to November
